I should probably say this out loud, because I‚Äôve realized not everyone reads these posts the way I mean them.

I don‚Äôt write this way because I enjoy circling my own thoughts or replaying the same ideas over and over. If anything, that habit nearly killed me once. I know what rumination looks like from the inside. I know how it feels when thinking becomes a stall instead of a movement.

Just to be clear about terms‚Äîbecause most people don‚Äôt use this word in everyday conversation‚Äîrumination is when your mind keeps replaying the same thought, memory, or problem over and over without it ever leading to action, relief, or change. It‚Äôs thinking that goes nowhere. It‚Äôs not reflection.  It‚Äôs a slow mental torture that feels responsible while it‚Äôs happening. It‚Äôs the sober version of this drink won‚Äôt hurt me this time. Same selective amnesia. You reopen the same thought the way you used to pour the same drink, take the same drug‚Äîconvinced that awareness alone has changed the outcome. It hasn‚Äôt. The mind just found a new virtual substance to use.

Addiction used to say, I‚Äôm not out of control‚ÄîI‚Äôm managing.

Different words. Same mechanism.

But nothing actually moves. You don‚Äôt arrive anywhere. You just wear a deeper groove into your mind. Like rocking in a chair and calling it working out.¬π

What I‚Äôm trying to do here on my account is something different.

Over the years‚Äîlong before I had language for it‚ÄîI learned that most of the damage in my life didn‚Äôt come from dramatic collapses. It came from drift. Quiet shifts. Small internal permissions. Slight changes in tone that felt reasonable at the time. Nothing I would‚Äôve confessed. Nothing I would‚Äôve flagged as a problem. Just a steady slide that only made sense once I was far from where I started.

The trouble was, I couldn‚Äôt see it while it was happening. I couldn‚Äôt feel it as danger. It felt like logic. Like self-care exercises. Like growth and wisdom, even.
That‚Äôs why I write with so much spiraling detail, and why I let the thought process show instead of summarizing it neatly at the end. 

I‚Äôm not trying to make a point as much as I‚Äôm trying to expose the patterns.
